This is already supported through the public `useThemeProps` API and the `styled` utility.

```tsx
import { styled, useThemeProps } from '@mui/material/styles';

const MyAlertRoot = styled('div', {
  name: 'MyAlert',
  slot: 'Root',
})(({ theme }) => ({
  padding: theme.spacing(1),
}));

export function MyAlert(inProps) {
  const props = useThemeProps({
    props: inProps,
    name: 'MyAlert',
  });

  return <MyAlertRoot {...props} />;
}
```

With `name: 'MyAlert'` and `slot: 'Root'`, `styled` resolves `theme.components.MyAlert.variants` and `styleOverrides`; `useThemeProps` merges `theme.components.MyAlert.defaultProps`.

```ts
createTheme({
  components: {
    MyAlert: {
      defaultProps: { variant: 'dashed' },
      variants: [
        {
          props: { variant: 'dashed' },
          style: { border: '2px dashed currentColor' },
        },
      ],
      styleOverrides: {
        root: { borderRadius: 8 },
      },
    },
  },
});
```

For TypeScript, augment your theme/component prop types so your custom component key and variants are recognized.
